  "summary": "Virginia Reeve introduces Anthony Kidd to the Earl of Carrington, claiming Anthony is an old friend she met in London. This social maneuver allows Anthony to transition from a suspicious stranger to an accepted guest at Chimney House. Privately, Anthony reflects on a gun he has hidden in a willow grove. During a walk by the lake, Virginia suggests that the murder at the estate is George Romax's fault for inviting the current guests. Anthony tells the police chief that staying at the estate will allow him to monitor George, a prospect the chief finds pleasing.\n\nAfter lunch is signaled by gongs, the Earl invites the guests to his study for drinks before they move to the dining room. During this time, Virginia whispers to Anthony that she convinced the Duke of Cambridge to show her the body and expresses her belief that Michael Prince is the killer. Anthony expresses interest in seeing the tutor, whom he believes is the woman living in the second room, though she is reportedly suffering from a headache.\n\nThe lunch is somber and uncomfortable. Following the meal, Bandler mentions that George will take a foreign delegation to a monastery to discuss national affairs. Mr. Fitch questions Anthony about the victim's identity, which Anthony evasively identifies as Count Stanislaus. Mr. Fitch criticizes the local constable's lack of initiative regarding the house lockdown and suggests the killer must have entered through an unlocked window. The passage concludes with Mr. Fitch departing to speak with the Earl.",
